             - he is a <rs id="t18310217-160-viclabel964" type="occupation">shoemaker</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18310217-160-victim1594 t18310217-160-viclabel964"></join>. On the 27th of January I was in our parlour, at nine o'clock in the morning; I saw the prisoner leaning over the counter; he appeared to be reaching for something - I went up to him, and asked what he wanted; he made no answer - I said he should not go out till he told me what he had in his apron - he then said it was a pair of boots which he was going to mend; he opened his apron - I said he had taken them from the counter; he said I was wrong, he had bought them in coming down the street for 1s. 6d.; I detained him till my husband came, and then he said he had bought them in Holborn - my cousin came out of the parlour, and stood against the door till my husband came in.</p>
               <p>
            
